## Summary Table

| Point | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---|---|---|
| State (instance fields) | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (only `public static final` constants) |
| Constructor | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Method access modifiers | Any (`private`, `protected`, `public`) | Only `public` (except Java 9 `private` methods for internal reuse) |
| Inheritance | Single (`extends` one class) | Multiple (`implements` many) |
| Method body | Abstract + concrete methods | Java 8+: `default` & `static` methods; Java 9+: `private` methods too |
| Represents | "IS-A" — identity + shared state/behavior | "CAN-DO" — capability/contract |

---

## One-Liner Answer
> "Both can't be instantiated. Abstract class = state + constructor + single inheritance ('is-a'). Interface = no state, no constructor, multiple inheritance ('can-do') — even with default/static/private methods added in Java 8/9."

## Trap Question
**Q: "Interface has method bodies now, so isn't it same as abstract class?"**
**A:** "No — still no state, no constructor, supports multiple inheritance. That's the dividing line."
